    "category": "AI-Native Engineering",
    "summary": "A file upload API passed basic tests but collapsed on large files. The fix was S3 multipart upload and transfer acceleration — but the real gap was the assumptions AI-generated code never questions.",
    "content": "\nRecently I reviewed a file upload API that was part of a larger data processing pipeline.\n\nThe design was straightforward:\n\n```text\nClient\n  ↓\nLambda generates pre-signed URL\n  ↓\nClient uploads to S3\n  ↓\nProcessing pipeline\n```\n\nAt first glance, everything looked reasonable. The Lambda generated pre-signed URLs, clients uploaded directly to S3, and uploaded files flowed into downstream processing.\n\nBasic testing passed.\n\nAs part of my review, I started validating larger file uploads.\n\nThat's when the issues appeared.\n\nLarge uploads were extremely slow and frequently timed out.\n\nThe implementation worked for smaller files, but began to struggle as file sizes increased. After investigating the upload flow and testing different scenarios, it became clear that the solution had never been validated against realistic file sizes and network conditions.\n\nTo support larger uploads, I implemented S3 Multipart Upload and enabled S3 Transfer Acceleration. Multipart upload allowed large files to be transferred in parallel and retried at the part level, while Transfer Acceleration improved performance for geographically distributed clients.\n\nThe result was a more reliable and scalable upload path that could handle larger files without the performance and timeout issues observed during testing.\n\nThe interesting lesson, however, wasn't about S3 features.\n\nIt was about assumptions.\n\nThe original implementation solved the problem it was designed to solve: upload a file.\n\nWhat it never appeared to ask was:\n\n* How large can the file become?\n* What happens when uploads take minutes instead of seconds?\n* How does the system behave on slower networks?\n* How will performance change as data volume grows?\n\nThose questions don't usually appear in generated code.\n\nThey appear during validation.\n\nOne thing I've noticed while reviewing AI-generated implementations is that the code itself is often reasonable. The gaps tend to appear in the specification, constraints, testing strategy, and scalability assumptions surrounding the code.\n\nAI can generate a working implementation.\n\nEngineering begins when we verify whether it still works outside the happy path.\n",
    "contentHtml": "<p>Recently I reviewed a file upload API that was part of a larger data processing pipeline.</p>\n<p>The design was straightforward:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-text\">Client\n  ↓\nLambda generates pre-signed URL\n  ↓\nClient uploads to S3\n  ↓\nProcessing pipeline\n</code></pre>\n<p>At first glance, everything looked reasonable. The Lambda generated pre-signed URLs, clients uploaded directly to S3, and uploaded files flowed into downstream processing.</p>\n<p>Basic testing passed.</p>\n<p>As part of my review, I started validating larger file uploads.</p>\n<p>That&#39;s when the issues appeared.</p>\n<p>Large uploads were extremely slow and frequently timed out.</p>\n<p>The implementation worked for smaller files, but began to struggle as file sizes increased. After investigating the upload flow and testing different scenarios, it became clear that the solution had never been validated against realistic file sizes and network conditions.</p>\n<p>To support larger uploads, I implemented S3 Multipart Upload and enabled S3 Transfer Acceleration. Multipart upload allowed large files to be transferred in parallel and retried at the part level, while Transfer Acceleration improved performance for geographically distributed clients.</p>\n<p>The result was a more reliable and scalable upload path that could handle larger files without the performance and timeout issues observed during testing.</p>\n<p>The interesting lesson, however, wasn&#39;t about S3 features.</p>\n<p>It was about assumptions.</p>\n<p>The original implementation solved the problem it was designed to solve: upload a file.</p>\n<p>What it never appeared to ask was:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>How large can the file become?</li>\n<li>What happens when uploads take minutes instead of seconds?</li>\n<li>How does the system behave on slower networks?</li>\n<li>How will performance change as data volume grows?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Those questions don&#39;t usually appear in generated code.</p>\n<p>They appear during validation.</p>\n<p>One thing I&#39;ve noticed while reviewing AI-generated implementations is that the code itself is often reasonable. The gaps tend to appear in the specification, constraints, testing strategy, and scalability assumptions surrounding the code.</p>\n<p>AI can generate a working implementation.</p>\n<p>Engineering begins when we verify whether it still works outside the happy path.</p>\n",
